The high detection capability of the LRL−AuNCs such as high selectivity and sensitivity established a reliable approach to determine Cu2+ in the cells. For further biosensing, the biocompatibility of LRL−AuNCs was investigated with an MTT assay. In the presence of AuNCs with a concentration of 10 to 300 μM, the cell survival rate was measured to be greater than 75% after incubation for 24 h (Fig. 5
                        ). The results suggest that the LRL−AuNCs probe had low cytotoxicity and good biocompatibility, which could be exploited in cellular imaging. Therefore, we assessed whether LRL−AuNCs probe could report changes of Cu2+ concentration in tumor cells by TPPL imaging. Since the two-photon microscope uses visible light or near-infrared light as the excitation light source, this wavelength of light has little light damage to living cells and tissues which is suitable for long-term detection. Compared with ordinary fluorescence imaging, TPPL imaging also has the advantages of deeper penetration, high resolution, and high image contrast. The following is the specific operation. Firstly, the fluorescent probe (250 μM) was incubated with A549 cells for 3 h, and then treated with two different concentrations of Cu2+ for 30 min for further imaging. The cells treated with LRL−AuNCs along exhibited a clearly red fluorescence (Fig. 6
                        A), implying that the nanoprobe LRL−AuNCs had entered the
